'''Edythe Danick London''' (born September 14, 1948)<ref>[http://books.google.com/books?id=6YNUAAAAMAAJ&q=%22London,+Edythe%22+AND+%221948%22&dq=%22London,+Edythe%22+AND+%221948%22&hl=en&ei=JInETbi_K4PB0QG0zM2WCA&sa=X&oi=book_result&ct=result&resnum=3&ved=0CDAQ6AEwAg American men & women of science], [[Google Books]], retrieved 01 August 2012</ref> is The Thomas and Katherine Pike Professor of Addiction Studies, and Director of the UCLA Laboratory of Molecular Pharmacology at the [[David Geffen School of Medicine]] [[University of California at Los Angeles]]. London received her Ph.D. in [[Pharmacology]] from the [[University of Maryland]] (Baltimore).  She did a post-doctoral fellowship at [[Johns Hopkins University]] School of Medicine.<ref>[http://www.semel.ucla.edu/profile/edythe-london bio of London from UCLA med school]</ref>

Prior to joining the UCLA faculty she was a Senior Scientist at the [[National Institute for Drug Addiction]] for 23 years and a member of the faculty at the [[Johns Hopkins University School of Medicine]].  She is known internationally for her work on [[drug addiction]] as well as other addictive disorders, such as tobacco and nicotine dependence.  She has been a pioneer in the development and use of advanced brain imaging techniques to study the effects of drugs, tobacco and other substances of abuse on brain function, including nuclear medicine studies such as Positron Emission Tomography (PET), and Functional Magnetic Resonance Imaging (fMRI). Her UCLA laboratory is engaged in a wide range of scientific studies as well as the development and testing of new medications.  The medication development projects in her laboratory utilize primates and other animals. The [[Web of Science]] lists several hundred articles published in [[peer-reviewed journals]] that have been cited over 13,000 times, leading to an [[h-index]] of 63.<ref>[[Web of Science]], accessed January 29, 2013.</ref>

Her house in Beverly Hills, California was vandalized on October 23, 2007, in an attack claimed by a domestic terrorist group, the [[Animal Liberation Front]] by breaking a window of the house and inserting a [[garden hose]] which flooded the house. Over $50,000 damage was reported.<ref>"Animal-Rights Militants Vandalize UCLA Researcher's House" By JJ Hermes [http://chronicle.com/daily/2007/10/548n.htm Chronicle of Higher Education] Tuesday, October 30, 2007</ref> Subsequently, her house was again attacked and damaged by a firebomb left at the front door on Tuesday, February 5, 2008. No one was home at the time. A statement issued by the [[North American Animal Liberation Press Office]]<ref>{{cite press release |publisher=North American Animal Liberation Press Office |date=February 6, 2008 |title=UCLA Vivisector Gets Return Visit from Animal Liberationists |url=http://www.animalliberationpressoffice.org/press_releases/pr_08_02_06_londonburns.htm |accessdate=2009-08-20 |archiveurl=http://web.archive.org/web/20080211103245/http://www.animalliberationpressoffice.org/press_releases/pr_08_02_06_londonburns.htm |archivedate=2008-02-11}}</ref> claimed that animal liberationists were responsible for placing the device.<ref>"UCLA Professor's House Is Firebombed" [http://chronicle.com/news/article/3891/ucla-professors-house-is-firebombed Chronicle of Higher Education] February 6, 2008</ref>

